    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.40-41_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">40</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">H. M. DENNY, M. D.
                        <lb/>
                    UNITED BANK BUILDING   
                        <lb/>
                    UNION, MO.</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 21, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Route 7</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>This note has been too long delayed. I was tremendously pleased to hear from you and even more pleased to know that there are those who can accept the unusual without scientific subterfuge.</p>
                
                <p>Since I do know that Mrs. Neihardt is no longer here I would like to express such condolences as I may offer.</p>
                
                <p>We would like to urge that you do drop in to see us and I know that a visit from you would be good for us. We do not live with pretensions and it <del>w</del><add>c</add>ould be that you would find some measure of peace and relaxation here at this time.</p>
                
                <p>We have a big little home which has seen a lot of living, a few antiques and quite a bit of evidence that the Indians were hereabouts.</p>
                
                <p>Sidney, age 17 and our youngest, has found about half of the Indian relics by himself. For me, his most astounding find was a burnished pot with five arrows which he picked up from a rocky ledge in a small cave.</p>
                
                <p>Sid has some inclination for archeology. I believe that we could use some advice on that. We speak of a future in a certain vocation but if pressed for a definition of the same I know that I could not give one. On reflection I wonder if the future is not perhaps a pleasure in the doing?</p>
                
                <p>Our idea of luxury is either to sit at home or to stash a little grub in the car and to take off for the farm on the Meramec (Catfish in the Indian language?). The Indians were there at one time in great profusion and I believe that they must have had an eye for beautiful country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>HM. Denny</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>Short notice or no notice, either one will be sufficient.</p>
                </postscript>
                
